This isn&#39;t a compiler bug at all, it&#39;s just a result of how Jackson implements `TypeReference` (although I suppose it&#39;s caused by a limitation of Java).

When you write `new TypeReference&lt;T&gt;() {};`, the compiler rewrites that to something like `new Foo$1();` where `Foo` is the name of the class your method is in. The generated anonymous class looks something like this. Note that if `T` is a type parameter to another method, the argument to `TypeReference` is a special `Type` that refers back to the original type parameter `T`.
```
class Foo$1 extends TypeReference&lt;T&gt; {}
```
