The `TypeReference` [constructor](https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-core/blob/2.13/src/main/java/com/fasterxml/jackson/core/type/TypeReference.java#L31) looks something like this:
```
protected TypeReference() {
  Type superClass = getClass().getGenericSuperclass();
  //_type is the type to construct. It should be UserConfig.class, DoodadConfig.class, etc.
  _type = ((ParameterizedType) superClass).getActualTypeArguments()[0];
}
```
So if the `T` above is a concrete type like `UserConfig`, everything&#39;s hunky-dory. `getClass()` will give you `Foo$1.class`, `getGenericSuperclass()` will give you a type representing `TypeReference&lt;UserConfig&gt;`, and `_type` will be `UserConfig.class`. Later on, when Jackson is reading an object, it sees that you want a `UserConfig` and not a `LinkedHashMap`, so it uses reflection to look at `UserConfig` and construct an object of that class.

However, if `T` is a type parameter, `_type` will be a [`TypeVariable`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/reflect/TypeVariable.html). Unfortunately, this `TypeVariable` cannot yield any information about what `T`&#39;s actual value was, at least as far as I can tell. This is because there is only one anonymous class that is generated, even if there are multiple instances of it. Since Java doesn&#39;t do monomorphization, all the `TypeReference&lt;T&gt;`s you create in your `optionalGenericConfigMapFromPath` method will be instances of the same exact class: `Foo$1`. The superclass of that is `TypeReference&lt;T&gt;`, which is erased to `TypeReference&lt;Object&gt;` because it&#39;s impossible for that `T` to point to every single `XConfig` class you have.

Because Jackson doesn&#39;t have any information about which class you want to construct an instance of, it just defaults to using a `LinkedHashMap`. Since that&#39;s obviously not the same as, say, `UserConfig`, you get a `ClassCastException` or something of that sort at runtime.

The compiler does infer the types correctly, but even if it didn&#39;t, it wouldn&#39;t matter because of the wacky way type erasure is handled. Since Jackson makes heavy use of reflection, these sort of weird things are probably more likely to happen. It&#39;s best if you pass either a `TypeReference&lt;T&gt;` or a `Class&lt;T&gt;` to the `optionalGenericConfigMapFromPath` method itself. You *are* already passing a `Class`, but even if it affected type inference, it&#39;s useless for the runtime stuff, so you&#39;ll have to give it as an argument to `GenericConfigMap` instead of `ref`, assuming that `GenericConfigMap`&#39;s constructor takes any `Type`, not just `TypeReference`s.

